Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:40.46,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fad(300,300)}We are accustomed to thinking of the universe in binary terms. On one side, there is the hard, measurable world of matter. On the other, the pure, unformed realm of spirit. But what happens in the space between? When you dream, when you experience a profound archetype, when a vision strikes you with the force of reality—where do these events actually take place? They are not physical, yet they are not mere illusions. They possess a weight, a texture, a geography. The philosopher Henry Corbin argued that to understand the human soul, we must map this missing middle. We must explore the world between worlds.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.46,0:01:20.45,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fad(300,300)}Corbin calls this intermediate region the Mundus Imaginalis, the 'alam al-mithal. It is crucial to distinguish the 'imaginal' from the 'imaginary'. The imaginary is the unreal, the fake, the product of mere fantasy. The imaginal, however, is a concrete, spiritual world. It is as real as the physical world, but perceived by a different organ. Corbin maps this as the 'eighth clime', a mystical Earth called Hurqalya, situated beyond our physical geography. It is the realm where what is bodily becomes spirit, and what is spiritual acquires a body. It is the suprasensory Orient, the true north of the soul.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.45,0:02:01.30,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fad(300,300)}But how do we perceive this world? Not with our physical eyes, which are bound to the sensory universe. We perceive it through the 'active Imagination'. This is not passive daydreaming; it is a rigorous, visionary apperception. It requires the opening of the inner eye, the removal of the veil that darkens it. When this eye opens, the five physical senses are transmuted. And what does this inner eye see? Corbin, drawing on the mystic Shahid, describes a vision of pure green. Green is the color that outlasts the others. It is the light of the emerald cities of Hurqalya, reflecting suprasensory realities.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.30,0:02:40.32,Quote,,0,0,0,,{\fad(300,300)}In this imaginal realm, the seeker eventually encounters a specific presence. Corbin recounts a profound narrative of a seeker who wished to understand the mystery of Creation. He descended into a subterranean vault, filled with darkness and howling winds. Suddenly, a figure of breathtaking beauty appeared in his sleep and spoke to him. 'Take a lamp,' the figure said, 'and place it under a glass to shield it from the winds; then it will give thee light in spite of them.' The seeker, trembling, asked: 'Who then art thou?' The figure answered: 'I am thy Perfect Nature. If thou wishest to see me, call me by my name.'
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.32,0:03:21.53,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fad(300,300)}It is vital to understand what this Perfect Nature is not. It is not a psychological 'double', nor is it the Jungian shadow. The shadow belongs to the lower psyche, the dark envelope of the ego that must be burned away. The Perfect Nature is a celestial, transcendent counterpart. It is your angel, conjoined with your star. Corbin expresses their relationship through a mathematical formula: not one equals one, which is the trap of abstract monism where everything blurs into a single blob. But rather, one times one. Two distinct entities, perfectly reflecting each other, maintaining their boundaries while acting in absolute unity.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.53,0:04:02.28,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fad(300,300)}How, then, does one actually meet this Guide of light? It is not achieved by passive waiting, but through the active fire of spiritual practice. In the Sufi tradition, this is the dhikr, the remembrance of the divine. The mystic Najm Kobra visualized this practice as a pure, ardent blaze. As the mystic breathes out the names of God, they exhale flames of fire. From the height of heaven, the Guide breathes fire back. The two flames meet. This fire consumes the dark envelope, the lower ego, and illuminates the darkness. If light is already there, the two lights associate, and there is light upon light.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.28,0:04:37.73,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fad(300,300)}When the veil is finally lifted, what is the nature of this meeting? It is a relationship of perfect, dynamic reflection. Corbin describes it beautifully: 'My image looks at me with my own look; I look at it with its own look.' In this state, the seeker and the Guide become an unus-ambo, a one-two. Each simultaneously assumes the position of the 'I' and the 'self', the image and the mirror. You are not losing yourself in a vast, impersonal cosmic ocean. You are meeting your own deepest, most authentic reality, looking back at you with a face of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.73,0:05:15.62,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fad(300,300)}The world between worlds is not an escape from reality; it is the bridge that makes reality meaningful. It is the realm where our deepest visions, our highest aspirations, and our personal angels take on form and substance. The next time you close your eyes and see the darkness, remember that the darkness is merely the canvas. According to whether what appears to you is light or darkness, your witness is light or darkness. Guard your inner eye. Nurture the fire. For in the end, as the mystics remind us, green is the color that outlasts the others. And from this color, the true light begins.
